tial of the novel's many theatrical spinoffs even in the Jim Crow era, Uncle Tom's breezy disavowal by prominent voices of the Harlem Renaissance, and a developing critique of "Uncle Tom roles" in Hollywood. Within the stubborn American binary of black and white, citizens have used this rhetorical figure to debate the boundaries of racial difference and the legacy of slavery. Through Uncle Tom, black Americans have disputed various strategies for racial progress and defined the most desirable and harmful images of black personhood in literature and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literaturexHistory. 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aAmerican literaturexSocial aspects. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature . 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literaturexHistory. 4aHarriet Beecher Stowe. 4aHollywood. 4aNew Negro. 4aOld Negro. 4aadaptation. 4acharacter. 4aprotest. 4aslavery. 4atheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aGates, Henry Louis08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360609840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606098.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles